05147nam a22006975i 9780822386841DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20052005ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1226678316  a97808223868417 a10.1515/97808223868412doi  a(DE-B1597)552915  a(OCoLC)1055293274  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aGN41.8b.U58 2005 7aSOC0020002bisacsh00aUnwrapping the Sacred Bundle :bReflections on the Disciplining of Anthropology /ced. by Daniel A. Segal, Sylvia J. Yanagisako. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (184 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tRearticulating Anthropology -- tUnchosen Grounds: Cultivating Cross-Subfield Accents for a Public Voice -- tFlexible Disciplinarity: Beyond the Americanist Tradition -- tLanguages/Cultures Are Dead! Long Live the Linguistic-Cultural! -- tAn Archaeology of the Four-Field Approach in Anthropology in the United States -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLively, forceful, and impassioned, Unwrapping the Sacred Bundle is a major intervention in debates about the configuration of the discipline of anthropology. In the essays brought together in this provocative collection, prominent anthropologists consider the effects of and alternatives to the standard definition of the discipline as a “holistic” study of humanity based on the integration of the four fields of archaeology, biological anthropology, sociocultural anthropology, and linguistic anthropology. Editors Daniel A. Segal and Sylvia J. Yanagisako provide a powerful introduction to the volume. Unabashed in their criticism of the four-field structure, they argue that North American anthropology is tainted by its roots in nineteenth-century social evolutionary thought.The essayists consider the complex state of anthropology, its relation to other disciplines and the public sphere beyond academia, the significance of the convergence of linguistic and cultural anthropology, and whether or not anthropology is the best home for archaeology. While the contributors are not in full agreement with one another, they all critique “official” definitions of anthropology as having a fixed, four-field core. The editors are keenly aware that anthropology is too protean to be remade along the lines of any master plan, and this volume does not offer one. It does open discussions of anthropology’s institutional structure to all possible outcomes, including the refashioning of the discipline as it now exists.Contributors. James Clifford, Ian Hodder, Rena Lederman, Daniel A. Segal, Michael Silverstein, Sylvia J. Yanagisako  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAnthropological linguistics. 0aAnthropologistsxEducation. 0aAnthropologistsxTraining of. 0aEthnoarchaeology. 0aEthnology. 0aPhysical anthropology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aClifford, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClifford, James.1 aHodder, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLederman, Rena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLederman, Rena.1 aSegal, Daniel A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSegal, Daniel A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSilverstein, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYanagisako, Sylvia J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYanagisako, Sylvia J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe